          "body": "Four times the chapter names Shiloh as the place where this all happens (18:1, 8, 9, 10). The Tent of Meeting has been moved from Gilgal — Israel's entry-point foothold — to the interior of the land. This relocation is more than logistical. Gilgal marked the beginning of conquest; Shiloh marks the beginning of settlement. The presence of God has advanced into the land along with His people. Every lot is cast specifically 'before the LORD' (*liphnei Adonai*, 18:6, 8, 10) — not at a tribal council, not before a military commander, but in the presence of the covenant God at His dwelling. This framing transforms what might otherwise look like a real-estate division into a liturgical act. The land is not being parceled out by human agreement; it is being received from the divine Landlord. Psalm 78:54-55 captures the theology: 'He brought them to His holy land, to this mountain which His right hand had gained. He also drove out the nations before them and apportioned them for an inheritance by measurement.' The *measurement* at Shiloh is the fulfillment of the *promise* made to the patriarchs — and it happens in God's presence, on His terms."
