          "body": "Joshua 18 does not end with a sermon; it ends with a city list. Yet the chapter's pastoral argument is unmistakable, and the New Testament writers heard it. Hebrews 3-4 — the NT's most sustained engagement with the Joshua generation — uses Canaan as the type for the believer's 'rest' (*katapausis*) and warns in precisely the same terms as Joshua 18:3: 'Do not harden your hearts' (Heb 3:8), 'Let us be diligent to enter that rest' (Heb 4:11). The warning in Hebrews 4:1 — 'a promise remains of entering His rest, let us fear if any one of you may seem to have come short of it' — is the New Covenant version of *raphah*: the covenant people standing passively before a gift already theirs. The application is not merely devotional. It is doctrinal: there is a class of covenant blessing that God has already secured and legally granted but that requires active, disciplined, costly entrance on the part of the recipient. The seven tribes' failure at Shiloh is not primarily a failure of effort; it is a failure to believe that the gift is real enough, valuable enough, and urgent enough to warrant the effort of possession."
